.TH "Math.tan" "JS" "February 21, 2023" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Math.tan \- Math.tan()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Math.tan()\f[B]\f[R] static method returns the tangent of
a number in radians.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
Math.tan(x)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]x\f[R]
A number representing an angle in radians.
.SS Return value
The tangent of \f[CR]x\f[R].
If \f[CR]x\f[R] is \f[CR]Infinity\f[R], \f[CR]\-Infinity\f[R], or
\f[CR]NaN\f[R], returns \f[CR]NaN\f[R].
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Due to floating point precision, it\[cq]s not possible
to obtain the exact value π/2, so the result is always finite if not
\f[CR]NaN\f[R].
.RE
.SH DESCRIPTION
Because \f[CR]tan()\f[R] is a static method of \f[CR]Math\f[R], you
always use it as \f[CR]Math.tan()\f[R], rather than as a method of a
\f[CR]Math\f[R] object you created (\f[CR]Math\f[R] is not a
constructor).
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using Math.tan()
.IP
.EX
Math.tan(\-Infinity); // NaN
Math.tan(\-0); // \-0
Math.tan(0); // 0
Math.tan(1); // 1.5574077246549023
Math.tan(Math.PI / 4); // 0.9999999999999999 (Floating point error)
Math.tan(Infinity); // NaN
.EE
.SS Math.tan() and π/2
It\[cq]s not possible to calculate \f[CR]tan(π/2)\f[R] exactly.
.IP
.EX
Math.tan(Math.PI / 2); // 16331239353195370
Math.tan(Math.PI / 2 + Number.EPSILON); // \-6218431163823738
.EE
.SS Using Math.tan() with a degree value
Because the \f[CR]Math.tan()\f[R] function accepts radians, but it is
often easier to work with degrees, the following function accepts a
value in degrees, converts it to radians and returns the tangent.
.IP
.EX
function getTanDeg(deg) {
  const rad = (deg * Math.PI) / 180;
  return Math.tan(rad);
}
.EE
